segments.text: from, what kind of attitudes, income, urban, rural?
What I remember as being kind of interesting is how few people from Houston were at A&M, for sure from my high school.
There was only one other, I mean, my high school, you know, I had five or six hundred
People graduated from Lamar in 63, and only one other went to A&M other than the two twins that played footballs with us, four of us.
The two football players, and then myself and one other.
And I always...
you know, I kind of thought that was an interesting thing.

The Aggies, you know, I'd never heard of Muleshoe and, you know, Gosney was from Muleshoe and, you know, and Cut and Shoot and all these little places, you know, that I'd either heard about or not heard about.
If I'd heard about them, they took life.
And I felt at the time,
A&M, maybe because I was in ag-eco, veterinary medicine and ag-eco, so I was in the agriculture business and not in the engineering business and the nuclear business and some of the other programs.
But I felt that A&M was an agriculture, a rural-based school.
There were some people from Fort Worth and some from San Antonio, but really they were from the small towns across Texas.
And, you know, just were, you know, were just good, good solid people.
You know, I mean, I just always thought.
Was there any ethnic diversity in your outfit?
If there were, I do not remember anything.
even Hispanic in any of my outfits.
And there was definitely no black.
Jewish?
Well, not that I knew of.
I really didn't get to know Jewish people until I got into the Army.
And there weren't many in the Army, but that's where I remember meeting my first Jewish.
I mean, I was in the Army when I ate my first pizza.
Because if you ate pizza in Texas, you were in a beer hall.
Because pizza and beer went together.
I was a non-alcoholic, so I didn't go to those places.
And I remember I was at Fort Benning, Georgia, second lieutenant, when I ate my first pizza.
So I probably led a fairly...
protected life, you know, growing up and all that.
But now there were some Catholic and Protestant.
Yes, but because half of my family is Catholic and half is Methodist, and I went to catechism growing up, that, there's no, I never,
Matter of fact, I always thought it was interesting the debate over Kennedy being a Catholic on whether he should be president of the United States.
I couldn't imagine that debate.
I couldn't, I mean, all my cousins, half of my cousins, I'm one of 42 first cousins, half of them are Catholic, half of them are Methodist.
The two churches in our little town in Louisiana were next door to one another.
I mean, you know,
Some of those debates don't make any sense to me.
They didn't then, and they certainly don't now.
And as far as you were aware, the NM student body accepted people as individuals.
Yeah, and I mentioned early on the international students.
There were...
minority international students.
Most of them were Arab or Pakistani, so they weren't necessarily black.
But there was, especially in the College of Agriculture, there was a lot of international students.
And I was impressed that A&M was taking these people.
I thought that was a good deal.
And I went out of my way to befriend
you know, a lot of them and try to help them.
I mean, I wasn't in any clubs with them or any organizations, but in classes, if I saw one of them struggling or something and it was a class that I was doing well in, I would try to help them.
What did you and your buddies think were the most prestigious student positions?
Oh, well, there was no doubt.
I mean, you know, the Corps Commander was it.
I knew the wing commanders and the brigade commanders were important positions.
I felt the funnest positions, and I feel this today, were the company commander positions because that's where you're really getting, you know, there's no staffs down there.
You're just kind of interacting, and in the Army, you know, I commanded every position from platoon leader through Army three-star, and the most fun positions
Position was when other my two company commands.
I mean, that's where you're really You know, you know, everybody's first name Everything about them was there even a student body president then?
If there was I don't know I don't recall that I mean if you were the Corps commander you were the leader and being president senior class and
had some prestige.
But it was usually a core guy.
All right, what about your leaders?
What did you all think of your leaders?
Well, it was interesting.
I saw that on your question.
And Ted Hopgood, I'm having dinner tonight with Ted Hopgood, who I've always admired.
And he was two years ahead of me, and Ted was a squared-away guy.
But I always thought that tradition went a little far
when they wore short-sleeved shirts on some of those unbelievably cold, wet, bitter, icy football games.
Because I was sitting there with all the clothes I owned on and freezing to death, and there they were in their whites with their sleeves up.
And I said, you know, I don't think that's good judgment.
And so I remember saying, these guys, obviously, you know, there's a tradition here
But there has to be some common sense to this business.
But I always felt that they were, again, the Yells were very disciplined.
It's not nandy-pandy.
I mean, it's very professional, very predictable.
And I, even before I appreciated regimentation,
liked all that, so I always thought the Yell Ears.
I didn't want to be one.
That was not my personality to be out there in front of folks leading cheers, leading yells, but I remember admiring and respecting those guys.
What did you all think about the band?
Well, it's really interesting, and I've told this to Jeannie several times.
The band, when you're a cadet, they're BQs.
And you throw, you have deal fights, and you persecute them.
And the minute you graduate, they're the greatest thing about the symbol.
They are the symbol of Texas A&M when you may, you know, the score of the game may be 40 to nothing, but you won the halftime.
Nobody can compete with the band.
And so I haven't quite figured that out, how you could, you know,
persecute them so much when you're here and admire and respect them so much the day you leave.
I mean, it's the darndest thing.
But no, that was the truth.
And I was a musician.
I mean, I love music, and I wouldn't have been in the band if my life depended upon it.
But today, if a guy is halfway musically inclined and wants to come to A&M, I tell him, hey, get in the band.
Did you know...
That secret fraternities existed?
No.
You mean Greek fraternities?
No, no, no.
No, I wasn't on the inner circles of anything.
No, I didn't know any secrets.
The TTs and the stickers.
No, sir.
The stickers go back at least to Mr. Evans' day.
Wow.
Their symbol was the swastika.
Wow.
Which is far before the Nazis knew about it.
And the TTs were the true Texans, and apparently they still exist, and apparently they each have one goal, to get their members in the key positions of leadership on the campus.
Yeah, see, I was not a joiner.
Excuse me a minute, let me just... Let's see...
Traveled to and from College Station.
You went by car, but you also hitchhiked.
Yes.
Describe some hitchhiking experiences.
Well, when I went to Baylor, gas was 19 cents a gallon, but 19 cents was a lot of money.
And what was interesting, because it's in my journals, when I was at A&M, I was buying stock.
I was buying Halliburton, several stocks, as I indicated.
And so I was a frugal guy.
What my mother says, she would send me $50 and I'd put $25 in savings.
As a matter of fact, I was one of Dennis Gehring's, you know, one of his at the Bank of A&M.
That was my first account.
And I was a frugal guy.
And so 19 cents a gallon was a lot of money in my Jeep.
did not get very good gas mileage.
It was four-wheel drive, had a winch, front and rear, power takeoff winch.
So it was heavy.
It got eight or nine miles to the gallon.
And so when I would go up to Baylor to see Chuck Rosenthal, my best friend, I would hitchhike because it was so easy.
And I would just usually get a ride.
Billy Provine would give me a ride out

to Highway 6, you know, right in front of the administration building with the big oak trees, and I would just, and I'd have that guitar, and I still have the case, and I'd stand there, and I was not in uniform, but I swear the first car that would go by would stop, and, you know, and they'd say, how far are you going?
And I'd say, Waco.
Well, that was a look that
Sometimes it'd take four or five cars to get somebody that was going to Waco, because you had to change a couple times to get to Waco.
But I would get there fast, and I had my harmonica in the case and the guitar, and I would just play the whole way there.
Never any negative experiences?
No, never.
I don't recall anything.
I recall hitchhiking a lot, and I never recall having a bad experience.
And you didn't go by bus or train?
No, I didn't.
Again, because the farm was so close and I had that Jeep, I didn't go back to Houston very much because I would meet my family on the weekends.
you know, at the farm.
And you had a steady girlfriend, so you didn't have blind dates with Tessies.

No, and I didn't, you know, and I didn't travel to Austin, you know, I didn't, Jeannie and I were high school sweethearts, and so, and the folks would bring her up to the farm, and you know, she would come, she had that friend in Navasota, and
And so, you know, I didn't do much.
When she was here and other girls were here, how were they treated?
How were the young women treated then, the dates?
Well, everybody behaved themselves.
You know, there was, you know, and I guess we could ask Cheney, but I.
Were the big dances still going then?
Cotton ball, boop dance, ring dance.
Well, the ring dance was because I went to the ring dance, but I don't remember the cotton ball.
Jeannie loves to dance, and I'm not very good at that.
And I just...
Kind of like wearing sunglasses.
You know, I know I'm going to get car racks because real men didn't wear sunglasses and real men didn't dance.
And I just wasn't a dancer.
So I didn't do things like that.
You know, I wish I did.
Matter of fact, I...
I have a lot of little aches and pains now, and they're all from Texas football, every one of them.
They're not from the Army.
They're not from combat.
They're from getting broke up playing Texas football when you're too small and wanting to do good.
And I remember distinctly when I was 13, I was late to football practice, and I was never, ever late.
And the coach said, House, why are you late?
And I said, well, because the piano teacher kept me late.
And all my buddies ridiculed me, and the next day I quit piano.
And I tell folks I wish I'd have quit football, because I would be feeling a lot better now, and I would know I would still be playing the piano.
What did you and your buddies know about drugs?
I don't think anything.
Did you even know the words?
No.
Beer, matter of fact, I don't know anybody that drank hard liquor.
Aggies drank beer.
They may have drank too much for me, but that's as much as Aggies did.
I didn't know any Aggies that drank wine.
I didn't know any Aggies that drank bourbon or scotch.
They just drank a lot of beer, and I guarantee you, I didn't know anybody that took any kind of illicit drugs.
And the athletes didn't do anything for bigger muscles.
There was none of that.
And people smoked cigarettes.
Yes, but you know, it was interesting.
None of my friends smoked.
I don't have...
I don't have one recollection of a friend smoking.
Because I remember coming into the Army, and I was appalled that everybody smoked.
I mean, all the leaders, everybody.
And I never had smoked.
But I didn't have that same sensation at A&M.
So I don't.
I don't remember.
There was no ashtrays in my room or anything.
As far as you recall, did you even know the word heroin?
I don't think so.
Unfortunately, though, post-Vietnam in Germany, I became an expert.
I put 26 soldiers in the Federal Pen for heroin abuse from one rifle company in Baumholder, Germany.
Wow.
The notable people here on the campus, Mr. Rutter and so forth, did you know Old Army Lou?
No, but I knew who he was, and I knew, I mean, I knew, and Pinky.
Well, of course, we all knew Pinky, and we would all cheer, but I never...
See, again, to know those people, you had to be somebody, and I wasn't in any of those leadership positions, so you just didn't know them.
You knew who they were, and Pinky was kind of what A&M was all about.
He was always around.
All right, and that leads to a great A&M tradition, silver taps.
Do you remember by chance...
going to Silver Taps early in your...
Yes.
There's two memories I have of Silver Taps.
You know, I remember going to a couple and I didn't know the people, the person.
We didn't have too many.
I mean, we did not have very many Aggies that died.
But I remember the first time one of my friends was killed in a car wreck and going...
And I remember that one.
But what I remember about Silver Taps was the fact that it took precedence over everything else.
And when it was over, you walked back without talking, and there was no talking, and nobody that I ever knew violated that.
It was something above...
everything else.
And my oldest nephew, the number one grandson, and the nephew and the nieces, the one that was most like me, died here in a car wreck as a junior at A&M.
And my brother was from Tulane, and I was a lieutenant colonel at Fort Polk, Louisiana.
And my brother called me, and I immediately went on leave and helped.
It was an unbelievable tragedy.
But we, you know, there was going to be a silver taps for Curtis.
Curtis, Glenn Curtis House III.
And, hi, Ms. Chandler.
But, so I, you know, I...
I came from Fort Polk, Louisiana, picked up my brother in Houston, went to Austin, and we identified Curtis, and I did all that, and my brother was just in shock.
And then the silver taps was coming up, and he didn't know anything about silver taps, and I said, Glenn, trust me.
I mean, we've had a funeral.
We've had all these things, and you're not an Aggie.
but you'll never forget it, and it will help you.
And so I came back.
That was the first time I'd come back to A&M for years and years and years.
And I was flying a little Cessna then.
I had a little Cessna 182.
So I flew over, and I met Glenn, and we had dinner, matter of fact, at Dennis Gehring's.
Dennis had a big...
Wanda, Dennis, and Kay had a beautiful dinner for the house family because we came from all over.
And we went to Silver Taps, and I was so proud of the Aggies.
Because I told Glenn, I said, you know, Glenn, this was a tradition when we were small.
And it's so big now.
I don't know if these kind of traditions really hold, but I guarantee you it'll be nice.
Well, the Ross volunteers were perfect.
All the student body was perfect.
And when we left, and I had briefed his wife, who's a talker, and everybody else, when it's over, we don't talk.
I said, now, when we get back to the hotel rooms, I mean, you know, we can go ahead and talk.
But I said, there's no talking.
Well, nobody else, there was no students that talked.
I was so proud of the Aggies, I couldn't see straight.
And my brother to this day, I mean...
He may be the only non-Aggie to someday send money to A&M.
I mean, you know, he really, he's had two children.
He's had, his daughter's graduated from here, and then Curtis, of course, and then his other two sons graduated from Texas, but he loves Aggies.
And so, silver taps.

I mean, as important as Aggie mustard is, and boy, I've mustered in some strange places in the last 30 years, and I really, from Corregidor, I really think it's a great tradition, and maybe the greatest tradition because of my personal situation.
The silver taps is probably the tradition that, to me, must continue.
All right, Mustard.
Did you go to Mustard when you were a student?
Oh, every time.
Matter of fact, I... Where was it held?
G. Raleigh White.
Every time.
What did you think it symbolized?
Well, we were...
to the credit of the Corps, we were briefed on all of it.
We knew what it all was and the history of it.
Matter of fact, my focus is Civil War history.
My next focus is World War II European.
But I know a lot about Corregidor.
In my last three and a half years, I was in the Pacific.
But my...

My interest in the Philippines all started in 63 when they were preparing us for, you know, somebody in the company was given the mission, one of the upperclassmen, to prepare us for what muster was all about.
And I guess I've spoken at a dozen musters in the last 30 years.
And I've mustered in Vietnam.
I've mustered in Saudi Arabia.
I've mustered in Korea.
You know, sometimes with two or three Aggies, and sometimes with two or three hundred.
But it's quite a tradition.
And the musters where you had a friend die the year before, and you answer here, you know that man.
You knew that man.
There's like five musters where that happened.

And sometimes, unfortunately, the first time you know he died is when you get the muster packet, and I've been muster chairman a whole bunch, and so you go to the muster, and you're reading through, and you look at your group, and you see...
you know, one of your buddies that died, and then as soon as Muster's over, you get back and you start trying to figure out where it happened, how everybody is, the family and whatever.
So, no, it's, you know, there's some traditions there that other places will dream about.
Of the interviewees that I've talked to so far who were here before the war, World War II, almost none of them remember Muster.
Oh, okay.
Well, it, yeah.
It was a World War II.
It was a, Crickador is what, now, I don't.
It existed.
It existed, but that propelled it.
Yes, yes.
You know, and, you know, the sun never sets on an Aggie muster on the 21st of April.
That's right.
I mean, you know.
I've done, I think I've done 26 now.
Yeah.
Senior ring, when did you buy it, how much did it cost, where'd you get the money?
Well, I think it's all here.
Let me see if I'm, is it 66 or 67?
Probably 67, yeah, it'd be 67.
I just, I was looking through my journal and I found it.
God, I hope I can find it again.
I thought I marked it.
Let me see, maybe.
I just...
It had to be 67, and it was... And I thought I even stuck the pages, because I paid for my Aggie boots, the final payment for my Aggie boots, but it was in...
It was in the spring.
Oh, no, it'd be, yeah, 66 then.
Yeah, okay.
I graduated technically in January 20th of 68, and I'll read that to you.
That's kind of an interesting write-up.
But on the 19th of April, Tuesday, 1966, it was clear in College Station that
And they began early.
It's been a typical busy one.
Withdrew $25 from savings account and paid the balance on my senior boots and ordered my senior ring for $34.
It should get to me about July 5th or so.
And so here is the senior ring receipt, 3376.
And you had saved the money yourself.
Right.
And then I had been paying off.
I have holic boots, and there they are right there.
And I still ride.
What's amazing about my holic boots is I still have my pinks riding pants.
And when I do, late in life, I became a hunter-jumper.
And those are my colors.
And that's the boots you ride when you're doing fox hunting.
But you would ride those on Saturdays or Sundays.
But sometimes we would fox hunt on Wednesday afternoons.
And I would wear my Aggie pinks.
And my boots, those Aggie boots, and then I didn't, for some reason I must have had to turn in my midnight shirt, but I found another very deep green shirt.
And so those boots, I continue to wear them, but I have used Propritz polish since the day I got them, and they have no cracks whatsoever.
And I saddle soap them and keep them in good shape.
How did you feel when you first put that ring on or put those boots on?
Well, I remember, I think I remember more about the boots than the ring.
The ring, what I just, what was interesting about calf roping is I was, I had a ring once on my right hand and I came off the left side of the horse and
Because sometimes you'd come off the left, sometimes off the right, depending on the calf.
And the ring caught on the pommel, and I almost tore the finger off.
So I made a rule that any time I was working, I didn't have any rings on.
No rings, no watches.
I wore a watch and my button here.
So around heavy equipment, from the time I was about...
16, 15 or 16, I never wore rings.
So when you look at my ring, my Aggie ring, it still looks brand new.
Because I only wear it to church and to occasions, I don't wear it when I'm working.
So I never wore it with my military, my BDU uniform.
I would wear it
when I had a staff job, but I was fortunate that most of my career was in command positions, and I wore combat uniforms, and I wore no rings and no watches.
And so the Aggie ring, I just was, there was two things about the ring.
I didn't want to lose it.
I'd read all the stories, you know, going back to World War II and everything.
I didn't want anybody cutting my finger off in Vietnam, so I didn't even take it to Vietnam.
Didn't even take the ring.
I didn't take my wedding band, you know, and so two tours in Vietnam and just stayed at home.
The Gulf War, I didn't take it to the Gulf War.
And so it was something that I just didn't want to lose, you know.
Then you don't have any story, unique story, about somebody having seen it at an unusual place.
No, no.
It...
I just...
I read that and I thought about that and I don't, you know, because I was kind of trying to protect the ring versus having it with me all the time.
But the boots, I love boots.
I love leather.
And I always did.
And I wore my boots every single day of my senior year.
And they were always polished, and no fish ever touched them.
Now, did anybody tease you about it?
No.
But after a while, they noticed.
I always wore my boots, no matter rain, sleet, or snow.
And I think I may have been the only guy that always wore them every day.
And nobody tried to hide them for you?
Well, you've got to understand, I was living in my truck.
I was in H1 by then.
I was in the married company.
And I was living in the back of that pickup truck.
So, again, you know, probably of all the people you've interviewed, you know, Eddie Joe Davis still can't believe it.
To this day, he can't believe I lived in that truck all those years and all those months.
But, I mean, I would get those boots on and off by myself.
And the pickup, the camper was flush with the top of the cab.
So you couldn't stand up in the camper.
All right.
Now, where did you keep it parked?
Behind Guyon Hall.
Behind Guyon Hall.
And what I did is I was running all these cattle.
I was spending more time at the ranch.
You know, once you got to be a junior, you didn't have to march to chow anymore.
You know, if
You know, you didn't have to.
Every once in a while you had to march the troops to chow, and then that day you were on a roster.
And you had to, but you didn't have to march to chow.
You could just show up.
And so I was going to class, and as soon as class over, I'd go to the ranch.
And we had a house at the ranch.
I had those cattle.
I was always doing something.
And so after a while, I said, you know, I'm paying $450 a semester room and board, and I'm not eating at the mess halls, and I'm not even sleeping in my room, you know.
So I went to Captain Simmons, and I said, sir.
